The '''kererū''' ('''''Hemiphaga novaeseelandiae'''''), also known as '''kūkupa''' ([[Māori language#Northern dialects|northern Māori dialects]]), '''New Zealand pigeon''' or '''wood pigeon''', is a species of [[pigeon]] native to New Zealand. [[Johann Friedrich Gmelin]] described the bird in 1789 as a large, conspicuous pigeon up to {{convert|50|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length and {{convert|550|–|850|g|abbr=on}} in weight, with a white breast and iridescent green–blue plumage. Two subspecies have been recognised; the second—the [[Norfolk pigeon]] of [[Norfolk Island]]—became extinct in the early 20th century. Kererū pairs are [[Monogamy in animals|monogamous]], breeding over successive seasons and remaining together when not breeding. They construct nests with twigs in trees, with a single [[egg clutch]].

Found in a variety of habitats across the country, the kererū feeds mainly on fruits, as well as leaves, buds and flowers. Although widespread in both forest and urban habitats, its numbers have declined significantly since European colonisation and the arrival of invasive mammals, such as [[rat]]s, [[Stoats in New Zealand|stoats]] and [[Common brushtail possum in New Zealand|possums]]. However, the results of nationwide bird surveys indicate that there has been a significant recovery in the population in suburban areas. As of 2022, the [[IUCN Red List]] classifies the species as least concern, while the [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] (DOC) classifies the kererū as "not threatened" but [[New Zealand Threat Classification System#Qualifiers|conservation dependent]].

Considered a {{lang|mi|[[taonga]]}} (cultural treasure) to the [[Māori people]], the kererū was historically a major food source in [[Māori culture]]. However, due to the decline in its population, hunting is illegal. Customary use of kererū is restricted to the use of feathers and bones obtained from dead birds collected by DOC. This issue has received significant public and political attention, as some people argue that bans on kererū hunting are detrimental to Māori traditions. In 2018, the kererū was designated [[Bird of the Year]] by the New Zealand organisation [[Forest & Bird]], and in 2019, the exoplanet [[Kererū (planet)|HD 137388 b]] was renamed Kererū in its honour.

== Taxonomy and nomenclature==
=== History and binomials===
English ornithologist [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] wrote about the kererū in his ''A General Synopsis of Birds'' in 1783 but did not give it a scientific name.<ref name="latham1783">{{cite book |last1=Latham |first1=John |author-link=John Latham (ornithologist) |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33730728 |title=General Synopsis of Birds |date=1783 |publisher=Benj. White |volume=2 |location=London, England |page=640 |access-date=21 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210921043810/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33730728 |archive-date=21 September 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref> German naturalist [[Johann Friedrich Gmelin]] gave it its first formal [[species description|description]] in 1789, placing it in genus ''[[Columba (bird)|Columba]]'' as ''C.&nbsp;novaeseelandiae'',<ref>{{Cite book |last=Gmelin |first=Johann Friedrich |author-link=Johann Friedrich Gmelin |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2656268 |title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae: secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis. |publisher=Impensis Georg Emanuel Beer |year=1789 |volume=1 |location=Leipzig, Germany |page=773 |language=Latin |access-date=21 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210921042625/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2656268 |archive-date=21 September 2021 |url-status=live |issue=2}}</ref> with Latham naming it ''Columba zealandica'' in his 1790 ''Index Ornithologicus''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Latham |first1=John |author-link=John Latham (ornithologist) |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/53510028 |title=Index ornithologicus |date=1790 |publisher=Leigh & Sotheby |volume=2 |location=London, England |page=603 |access-date=21 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210921114606/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/53510028 |archive-date=21 September 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[genus]] ''Hemiphaga'' was introduced by the French naturalist [[Charles Lucien Bonaparte]] in 1854 with the kererū (''Hemiphaga novaeseelandiae'') as the [[type species]] for that genus.<ref>{{cite journal | last=Bonaparte | first=Charles Lucien | author-link=Charles Lucien Bonaparte | year=1854 | title=Coup d'oeil sur les pigeons (deuxième partie) | language=French | journal=Comptes Rendus Hebdomadaires des Séances de l'Académie des Sciences | volume=39 | pages=1072–1078 [1076–1077] | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2820257 | access-date=15 October 2021 | archive-date=21 October 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211021100500/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2820257 | url-status=live }}</ref> The name combines the [[Ancient Greek]] {{transliteration|grc|hēmi}} meaning "half-" or "small", with the end of the genus name ''Carpophaga'', "fruit eating", as Bonaparte saw the genus as related to both that genus and ''Megaloprepia'' (now incorporated into ''[[Ptilinopus]]'').<ref name = "Fraser13">{{cite book | title = Australian Bird Names: A Complete Guide | first1 = Jeannie | last1 = Gray | first2 = Ian | last2 = Fraser | year = 2013 | location = Collingwood, Australia | publisher = CSIRO Publishing | page = 23 | isbn = 978-0-643-10470-9 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=W1TCqHVWQp0C&q=fraser+bird+names | access-date = 23 October 2021 | archive-date = 19 February 2022 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20220219204331/https://www.google.com.au/books/edition/Australian_Bird_Names/W1TCqHVWQp0C?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=fraser+bird+names&printsec=frontcover | url-status = live }}</ref>

===Subspecies===
[[File:Hemiphaga novaeseelandiae spadicea.png|right|thumb|The extinct [[Norfolk pigeon]] (''H. n. spadicea''), lithograph by [[John Gerrard Keulemans]] (1907), based on a preserved specimen in the [[Natural History Museum at Tring]]|alt=painting of a white and coloured pigeon]]
Two [[subspecies]] are recognised: ''H.&nbsp;n. novaseelandiae,'' which is found throughout New Zealand, and the little-studied [[Norfolk pigeon]] (''H. n. spadicea'') of [[Norfolk Island]], now [[Extinction|extinct]]. The subspecies differed in their plumage colour and shape.<ref name=hanzab>{{cite book | editor1-last = Higgins | editor1-first = P. J. | editor2 = Davies, S. J. J. F. | title = Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds: Volume 3: Snipe to Pigeons | year = 1996 | pages = 1016–1025 | url = https://nzbirdsonline.org.nz/sites/all/files/276_New%20Zealand%20Pigeon.pdf | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | location = Melbourne, Victoria | isbn = 978-0-19-553070-4 | access-date = 16 October 2021 | archive-date = 29 October 2021 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20211029110321/https://nzbirdsonline.org.nz/sites/all/files/276_New%20Zealand%20Pigeon.pdf | url-status = live }}</ref> In 2001, it was proposed that a third subspecies—''H.&nbsp;n. chathamensis'' or the [[Chatham Islands pigeon]]—should be raised to full [[species]] status as ''H.&nbsp;chathamensis'' on the basis of its distinct plumage, larger size and differing bone structure.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Millener|first1=P. R.|last2=Powlesland|first2=R. G.|date=2001|title=The Chatham Islands pigeon (Parea) deserves full species status; ''Hemiphaga chathamensis'' (Rothschild 1891); Aves: Columbidae|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand|language=en|volume=31|issue=2|pages=365–383|doi=10.1080/03014223.2001.9517659|issn=0303-6758|doi-access=free|bibcode=2001JRSNZ..31..365M }}</ref> This has since been widely accepted.<ref>{{Cite web|date=December 2009|title=Updates & Corrections – Clements Checklist|url=https://www.birds.cornell.edu/clementschecklist/updateindex/dec09overview/dec09/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210516010012/https://www.birds.cornell.edu/clementschecklist/updateindex/dec09overview/dec09/|archive-date=16 May 2021|access-date=23 January 2020|website=Cornell Lab of Ornithology | publisher=Cornell University}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=16 January 2008 |title=Species Updates – Version 1.5 |url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/updates/archives/species-v1/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210516010012/https://www.birds.cornell.edu/clementschecklist/updateindex/dec09overview/dec09/ |archive-date=16 May 2021 |access-date=23 January 2020 |website=World Bird List |publisher=International Ornithologists' Union}}</ref> Analysis of [[mitochondrial DNA]] confirmed the kererū and Norfolk pigeons to be more closely related to each other than to the Chatham pigeon, and that dispersal between the three landmasses most likely occurred during the [[Pleistocene]] Epoch.<ref name="Goldberg11">{{cite journal |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2699.2010.02414.x|title=Population structure and biogeography of ''Hemiphaga'' pigeons (Aves: Columbidae) on islands in the New Zealand region|year=2011|last1=Goldberg|first1=Julia|last2=Trewick|first2=Steven A.|last3=Powlesland|first3=Ralph G.|journal=Journal of Biogeography|volume=38|issue=2|pages=285–298|bibcode=2011JBiog..38..285G |s2cid=55640412 }}</ref>

===Classification===
The kererū belongs to the family [[Columbidae]], and the subfamily [[Ptilinopinae]], which is found throughout [[Southeast Asia]], [[Malay Peninsula|Malaya]], [[Australia]] and New Zealand. The members of this subfamily feed largely on [[fruit]]s, mainly [[drupe|stone fruit]].<ref name=":2" /> Within the subfamily, the kererū and Chatham Islands pigeon are in a [[clade]] with a lineage that has given rise to the [[topknot pigeon]] (''Lopholaimus antarcticus'') of Australia and the [[mountain pigeon]]s (''Gymnophaps'') of New Guinea, as shown in the cladogram below.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2010.04.016|title=Two aspects along the continuum of pigeon evolution: A South-Pacific radiation and the relationship of pigeons within Neoaves|year=2010|last1=Gibb|first1=Gillian C.|last2=Penny|first2=David|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=56|issue=2|pages=698–706|pmid=20399870|bibcode=2010MolPE..56..698G }}</ref>

